Well Evaluation
ND State 158-95-21-28-4TFH [SE SW Section 16, T158N-R95W] is located approximately 7.3
miles North of Tioga in McGregor County, North Dakota. The ND State 4TFH is a double-
section horizontal Three Forks well within the Williston Basin consisting of one ~10,000' long
lateral drilled to the south (176.57º). It expands the existing McGregor Field. The curve will be
kicked off in the Lodgepole and landed within the Three Forks Formation. Directional drilling
and geo-steering techniques will then be used to maintain maximum exposure to the target zone.
GEOLOGY
Lithology
Lithologic descriptions and sample analysis began in the Kibbey Formation.
Observed
formation tops were used to project a vertical depth for curve landing.
The Three Forks Formation (First bench) was logged at 9,664' TVD (-7,169' MSL). It consists
primarily of tan to cream colored argillaceous dolomite interbedded with light blue to green
shale. The target zone contained trace amounts of spotty brown oil staining. The Three Forks
Formation First Bench was the target reservoir for the lateral portion of the well (Picture 1).
Picture 1. Three Forks Formation (Carl Settle, Sunburst well site geologist)
Gas Monitoring
Background gas measured around 400u at the start of that lateral.
A gradual increase in
measureable gas led to the gas buster being utilized from 12,500' MD through the end of the
lateral. Background gas values peaked at approximately 800u in the vicinity of a small anticlinal
feature that ran from around 13,000-15,000' MD (Figure 1). From there, background gas
gradually declined back down to around 400u by the end of the lateral. The highest gas value
recorded was a connection gas show of 3,361u at 13,522' MD. The entire ideal target zone was
observed to contain relatively good gas concentrations and consistent oil staining. Fluorescence
throughout the lateral effort presented as slow, streaming yellow cuts.

Curve Landing
Data including gamma, rate of penetration (ROP), torque, and lagged samples were used to
determine marker and formation tops during the vertical hole and curve build section. During
both the vertical and curve, tops were compared to primary offset wells in order to ensure a
successful landing in the target zone. The true vertical depth (TVD) of the initial landing target
(9,666' TVD) was calculated by assuming comparable formation thicknesses from the Base Last
Salt to the landing target gamma signature. The initial landing target was tweaked as deeper
markers were observed, resulting in a final landing target of 9,674' TVD. The curve was landed
at 9,674' TVD (10,056' MD) near the top of the target interval on December 18, 2014.
Geosteering
The ideal target zone was defined as an 8' interval, the top of which was initially set at 9,674'
TVD; 13' below the base of the Lower Pronghorn (Figure 2). The most useful signature for
geosteering purposes was a warm gamma marker, reading 100-120 API, in the central portion of
the target interval.
The feature was bordered above and below by cooler gamma markers,
reading 40-50 API. This character established the gamma signature for the remainder of the
target interval. The formation was observed to be dipping downward most steeply (-0.8°) over
the first thousand feet of lateral drilling operations.
Dip gradually flattened out by around
12,500' MD. A slight upturn in formation dip (+0.4°) occurred at 13,500' MD. The formation
flattened back out again by 14,000' then turned downward (-0.45°) again at around 14,500' MD.
A more gentle downward dip (-0.1°) was observed from 15,900' to 17,800'. There, the dip
increased slightly to -0.25° where it remained until a TD of 20,015' was reached. The final gross
overall drop in TVD from entry of the Three Forks Formation to the end of the lateral was
estimated at 44' over 10,015' (0.25° down, Figure 2). The character of the lateral was similar to
offset wells, though the dip was less severe than expectations. The bottom-hole location is
calculated to be 10635.00' South & 637.93' East of surface location or approximately 251.12'
FSL & 2,621.93' FWL, SE SW Section 28, T158N, R95W. Geo-steering techniques exposed
96% of uncased wellbore within the primary Three Forks First Bench interval, with 65% of the
wellbore drilled within the established 8' Three Forks steering target. The well reached a TD of
20,015' on January 29, 2015.

SUMMARY
1)
The Liberty Management Resources, LLC. ND State 158-95-21-28-4TFH was re-entered
on December 11, 2014 and reached TD in 16.7 operational days on January 29, 2015.
2)
Samples from the Three Forks target consisted of primarily of argillaceous dolomite,
interbedded with shale.
The argillaceous dolomite presented trace intercrystalline
porosity. Oil shows in samples were visible as trace spotty brown oil stain yielding slow
streaming yellow fluorescent cuts.
3)
Fair gas shows were present throughout the well; most significant was a connection gas
show of 3,361u at 13,522' while drilling the lateral.
4)
The ND State 158-95-21-28-4TFH awaits completion operations to maximize its
production potential.
Respectfully submitted,
Carl Settle
Sunburst Consulting, Inc.
January 29, 2015

LITHOLOGY
ND State 158-95-21-28-4TFH
Rig crews caught 30' sample intervals from 7,370' to 10,056' and 50' sample intervals from 10,100-20,015' (TD).
Formation tops and lithologic markers have been inserted into the sample descriptions below for reference. Sample
descriptions begin in the Mississippian Kibbey Formation. Samples and were examined wet and dry under a binocular
microscope. Sample fluorescence cuts are masked by invert mud through intermediate casing. Quantifiers in order of
abundance are trace, rare, occasional, common and abundant.
Vertical Log Descriptions:
MD / TVD (MSL Datum)
7,370-7,400
SILTSTONE: red brown, tan, light gray-gray brown, sub blocky, friable-firm, earthy texture, slightly
calcareous, no visible porosity; SANDSTONE: cream-light pink, orange tan, very fine grain, sub angular, poor sorted,
friable, earthy texture
Kibbey Lime [Mississippian Big Snowy Group]
7417/7399 (-4,904')
7,400-7,430
LIMESTONE: cream-light gray, mudstone-wackestone, microcrystalline, blocky, firm-hard, crystalline, no
visible porosity, SILTSTONE: as above
7,430-7,460
SILTSTONE: light orange, light-medium orange brown, blocky, friable-firm, slightly calcareous,
anhydritic, sandy in part, no visible porosity; LIMESTONE: as above
7,460-7,490
SILTSTONE: light orange, light-medium orange brown, blocky, friable-firm, slightly calcareous,
anhydritic, sandy in part, no visible porosity
7,490-7,520
SILTSTONE: light orange, light-medium orange brown, blocky, friable-firm, slightly calcareous,
anhydritic, sandy in part, no visible porosity
7,520-7,550
SILTSTONE: light orange, light-medium orange brown, blocky, friable-firm, slightly calcareous,
anhydritic, sandy in part, no visible porosity
7,550-7,580
SILTSTONE: light orange, light-medium orange brown, blocky, friable-firm, slightly calcareous,
anhydritic, sandy in part, no visible porosity

trace LIMESTONE: cream-light gray, mudstone-wackestone, microcrystalline, blocky, firm-hard, crystalline

approval is granted on the condition that all portions of the well bore not isolated by cement, be no closer than
the 200' setback from the north & south boundaries and 500' setback from the east & west boundaries within the
2560 acre spacing unit consisting of Sections 9, 16 ,21, & 28 T158N-R95W.
PERMIT STIPULATIONS: Effective June 1, 2014, a covered leak-proof container (with placard) for
filter sock disposal must be maintained on the well site beginning when the well is spud, and must
remain on-site during clean-out, completion, and flow-back whenever filtration operations are
conducted. MWD survey frequency of 30 feet is required for any portion of the lateral that is within 500
feet of an existing vertical well that penetrates the Bakken pool. LIBERTY RES MNGMT CO must
contact NDIC Field Inspector Tom Delling at 701-770-8660 prior to location construction.
Drilling pit
NDAC 43-02-03-19.4 states that "a pit may be utilized to bury drill cuttings and solids generated during well
drilling and completion operations, providing the pit can be constructed, used and reclaimed in a manner that will
prevent pollution of the land surface and freshwaters. Reserve and circulation of mud system through earthen pits
are prohibited. All pits shall be inspected by an authorized representative of the director prior to lining and use.
Drill cuttings and solids must be stabilized in a manner approved by the director prior to placement in a cuttings
pit."
Form 1 Changes & Hard Lines
Any changes, shortening of casing point or lengthening at Total Depth must have prior approval by the NDIC.
The proposed directional plan is at a legal location. Based on the azimuth of the proposed lateral the maximum
legal coordinate from the well head is: 10685' south.
Location Construction Commencement (Three Day Waiting Period)
Operators shall not commence operations on a drill site until the 3rd business day following publication of the
approved drilling permit on the NDIC - OGD Daily Activity Report. If circumstances require operations to
commence before the 3rd business day following publication on the Daily Activity Report, the waiting period may
be waived by the Director. Application for a waiver must be by sworn affidavit providing the information
necessary to evaluate the extenuating circumstances, the factors of NDAC 43-02-03-16.2 (1), (a)-(f), and any other
information that would allow the Director to conclude that in the event another owner seeks revocation of the
drilling permit, the applicant should retain the permit.

message if after hours or on the weekend.
Survey Requirements for Horizontal, Horizontal Re-entry, and Directional Wells
NDAC Section 43-02-03-25 (Deviation Tests and Directional Surveys) states in part (that) the survey contractor
shall file a certified copy of all surveys with the director free of charge within thirty days of completion. Surveys
must be submitted as one electronic copy, or in a form approved by the director. However, the director may
require the directional survey to be filed immediately after completion if the survey is needed to conduct the
operation of the director's office in a timely manner. Certified surveys must be submitted via email in one adobe
document, with a certification cover page to certsurvey@nd.gov.
Survey points shall be of such frequency to accurately determine the entire location of the well bore.
Specifically, the Horizontal and Directional well survey frequency is 100 feet in the vertical, 30 feet in the curve
(or when sliding) and 90 feet in the lateral.
Surface casing cement
Tail cement utilized on surface casing must have a minimum compressive strength of 500 psi within 12
hours, and tail cement utilized on production casing must have a minimum compressive strength of 500 psi
before drilling the plug or initiating tests.
Logs NDAC Section 43-02-03-31 requires the running of (1) a suite of open hole logs from which formation tops and
porosity zones can be determined, (2) a Gamma Ray Log run from total depth to ground level elevation of the well bore, and
(3) a log from which the presence and quality of cement can be determined (Standard CBL or Ultrasonic cement evaluation
log) in every well in which production or intermediate casing has been set, this log must be run prior to completing the well.
All logs run must be submitted free of charge, as one digital TIFF (tagged image file format) copy and one digital LAS (log
ASCII) formatted copy. Digital logs may be submitted on a standard CD, DVD, or attached to an email sent to
digitallogs@nd.gov

WELL LOCATION PLAT
April 9, 2014
RE:
Filter Socks and Other Filter Media
Leakproof Container Required
Oil and Gas Wells
Dear Operator,
North Dakota Administrative Code Section 43-02-03-19.2 states in part that all waste material associated with
exploration or production of oil and gas must be properly disposed of in an authorized facility in accord with all
applicable local, state, and federal laws and regulations.
Filtration systems are commonly used during oil and gas operations in North Dakota. The Commission is very
concerned about the proper disposal of used filters (including filter socks) used by the oil and gas industry.
Effective June 1, 2014, a container must be maintained on each well drilled in North Dakota beginning when the
well is spud and must remain on-site during clean-out, completion, and flow-back whenever filtration operations
are conducted. The on-site container must be used to store filters until they can be properly disposed of in an
authorized facility. Such containers must be:
leakproof to prevent any fluids from escaping the container
covered to prevent precipitation from entering the container
placard to indicate only filters are to be placed in the container
If the operator will not utilize a filtration system, a waiver to the container requirement will be considered, but
only upon the operator submitting a Sundry Notice (Form 4) justifying their request.
As previously stated in our March 13, 2014 letter, North Dakota Administrative Code Section 33-20-02.1-01
states in part that every person who transports solid waste (which includes oil and gas exploration and production
wastes) is required to have a valid permit issued by the North Dakota Department of Health, Division of Waste
Management. Please contact the Division of Waste Management at (701) 328-5166 with any questions on the
solid waste program. Note oil and gas exploration and production wastes include produced water, drilling mud,
invert mud, tank bottom sediment, pipe scale, filters, and fly ash.
Thank you for your cooperation.
Sincerely,
Bruce E. Hicks
Assistant Director

3. Casing and cementing will be done to protect potentially productive
hydrocarbons, fresh water zones, abnormal pressure zones,
and prospectively valuable mineral deposits.
A. Casing head: 9 5/8" x 11" 5M multi-bowl w/ flange 22" below GL,Initial BOPE test to 5000 psi. unless 9 5/8" is pre set then SOW
Tubing head 11" 5M x 7 1/16" 10M. BOPE test to 5000 psi before drilling out 7" casing shoe.
B. Operators minimum specifications for pressure control equipment are shown on the attached BOP
schematic. After running surface casing and prior to drilling out, blind rams, pipe rams, manifold,
upper and lower kelly cock and safety valve will be pressure tested to 5000 psi. Hydril will be tested
to 2500 psi. Thereafter, the BOPE will be checked daily for mechanical operations and will be noted
in the IADC drilling reports. Before and after running the intermediate casing the BOPE will be tested
in the same manner. BOP will be tested at both high 5000 psi and low pressure to 250 psi.
Gas Buster will be fully rigged up and tested for fluid integrity, using anti-freeze solution
prior to drilling out surface casing.

10. Deviation & MWD Surveys
Surface Hole: 3 degrees max inclination & 1 deg/100' DLS maximum survey every 100' Min
Surface to KOP: Maintain Inclination less than 3 degrees. Adjust KOP as necessary.
Directional Surveys every 90' from surface to KOP.
MWD Surveys every 30' from KOP To landing 7" 90 ft surveys through horizontal.
GammaRay - Will be logged from KOP, through build section, and through lateral section.

D. Other Drilling Considerations & Lessons Learned:
1. Gas Buster- Not to be used for venting off flowline. Divert all flow to gas buster.
2. Lateral Drilling- Minimize DLS.
3. Salt Sections: Tight hole and stuck pipe may occur. Control drill +/-5' and back-ream
as necessary. Spot freshwater only if severely stuck.
4. Do not rotate PDC bit inside 7" casing while displacing well with kill weight fluids.
Ensure bit & motor are in open hole section.
5. Transfer OBM from storage tanks to rig tanks over the shaker screens.
6. CaCL Brine truck to location after running/cmt'g 7 inch csg. To be determined each well.

30 mmcfd with completion of planned line upgrade.

12 mmcfd ramping up to 24 mmcfd with completion of subject wells.

expand system in T158N R95W area with additional line to increase capacity to 30
mmcfd.

May 19, 2015.

for all wells being completed.

bopd and 2 mmcfd initial production rate average for 30 days with oil rate declining at
80% thereafter.
Anticipated Oil and Gas Rates and Duration (Multi-Well Pad):
Total production rate for six wells on pad will peak at 6000 BOPD and 12 mmcfd
expected initial production rate average for 30 days with oil rate declining at 80%
thereafter.

5. Amount of gas applicant is currently flaring.
a. Statewide percentage of gas flared (total gas flared/total gas produced) for existing
wells producing from the Bakken petroleum system. Note industry target goals are to
reduce flaring to 26% by 9-1-14, 23% by 1-1-15, 15% by 1-1-16, and 10% by 9-1-20:
Statewide percentage of gas flared for existing Liberty operated wells in June 2014 was
9%.
b. Field wide percentage of gas flared:
Fieldwide (McGregor Field) percentage of gas flared for existing Liberty operated wells
in June 2014 was 6%.
6. Alternatives to flaring.
a. Explain specific alternate systems available for consideration:
We have evaluated alternative gas utilization schemes including gas fired power
generation and pad processing to separate gas liquids.
b. Detail expected flaring reductions if such plans are implemented:
Based upon our existing gas connections and proximity to gas gathering lines and the
Tioga Gas Plant, we do not require additional options for flaring reductions.
